  'Gastronomy'
),
(
  'Tapas Trail: An Evening Crawl Through Portals Nous',
  'tapas-trail-portals-nous',
  'Portals Nous may be small, but its concentration of excellent tapas bars makes it perfect for an evening of grazing. Follow our curated route through the village''s best bites.',
  E'Portals Nous occupies a charming position between Puerto Portals and Bendinat, and its compact village centre holds a surprising number of quality tapas spots. This curated route works best starting around seven in the evening and should take approximately three hours at a comfortable pace.\n\n## Stop 1: Oliu\n\nBegin at this intimate wine bar on the main street. The selection of Mallorcan wines by the glass is exceptional, and the accompanying tapas board of local cheeses, sobrasada, and olives sets the right tone. Order a glass of the Anima Negra rosé and the pan amb oli with Ramallet tomatoes.\n\n## Stop 2: The Seafood Counter\n\nTwo doors down, a seafood-focused tapas bar offers the freshest gambas and calamari in the area. The secret is their direct supply from the Santa Ponsa fishing boats. The grilled octopus with pimentón and the fried baby squid are essential orders. Pair with a crisp local white.\n\n## Stop 3: The Japanese Crossover\n\nA newer addition to Portals Nous, this small corner restaurant blends Japanese precision with Spanish ingredients. The wagyu and jamón gyoza are a signature, and the nigiri using locally caught red prawn is outstanding. This is where the younger set gathers.\n\n## Stop 4: Casa Tradicional\n\nReturn to Mallorcan roots at this family-run establishment that has occupied the same premises for three decades. The tumbet, frito mallorquín, and cocas de trampó represent the island''s culinary heritage at its finest. Portions are generous and prices are honest.\n\n## Stop 5: The Nightcap\n\nEnd the evening at the cocktail lounge overlooking the small harbour. The bartender''s Mallorcan twist on classic cocktails incorporates local herbs, citrus, and almond liqueur. The terrace is heated in winter and open to the stars in summer.\n\n## Practical Notes\n\nPortals Nous is walkable from Puerto Portals in ten minutes. Taxis are readily available for the return journey. Reservations are not typically needed for tapas bars, but weekends in summer can be busy. Most places accept cards, but carrying some cash is advisable for the smaller establishments.',
  'https://images.pexels.com/photos/2664216/pexels-photo-2664216.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
  'Calvia Editorial',
  '2026-01-08T10:00:00Z',
  ARRAY['Gastronomy', 'Nightlife'],
  'Gastronomy'
),
(
  'Golf in Calvia: A Course-by-Course Guide',
  'golf-calvia-guide',
  'With three championship courses and several more within easy reach, Calvia is one of the Mediterranean''s premier golf destinations. Here is everything you need to know about playing in southwest Mallorca.',
  E'Calvia''s mild winter climate, stunning scenery, and concentration of quality courses make it an exceptional golf destination. Whether you are a low-handicap player seeking championship challenges or a social golfer enjoying the Mediterranean lifestyle, the area delivers.\n\n## Real Golf de Bendinat\n\nThe most centrally located of Calvia''s courses, Bendinat winds through a pine-clad valley with views of the sea and the Tramuntana mountains. The par-70 layout rewards accuracy over distance, with narrow fairways and well-defended greens. The clubhouse terrace is a favourite gathering spot for the Bendinat community. Green fees are moderate by Mallorcan standards, and membership offers excellent value.\n\n## Golf de Andratx at Camp de Mar\n\nDesigned by the legendary course architect F.W. Hawtree, this challenging mountain course occupies a spectacular setting above Camp de Mar. The elevation changes are dramatic, with several holes playing across deep ravines. The condition of the course is immaculate year-round, and the views from the elevated tees are among the finest in European golf.\n\n## Golf Santa Ponsa I, II, and III\n\nThe Santa Ponsa complex offers three distinct courses catering to all levels. Course I, the original championship layout, has hosted the Mallorca Classic on the European Tour. Course II provides a more accessible yet still engaging experience. Course III, the newest addition, incorporates modern design principles with environmental sensitivity.\n\n## The Winter Advantage\n\nWhile courses across northern Europe close for winter, Calvia''s courses remain in excellent condition year-round. November through March offers comfortable playing temperatures, reduced green fees at many courses, and no waiting on tees. Many European golf societies organise their annual trips to Mallorca during this period.\n\n## Practice and Coaching\n\nSeveral courses offer PGA-qualified coaching with instruction available in English, German, Spanish, and Swedish. The driving range at Santa Ponsa and the short game area at Bendinat are ideal for regular practice sessions.\n\n## Junior Golf\n\nCalvia''s courses run active junior programmes with structured coaching and competitive opportunities. The year-round playing season gives young golfers a significant developmental advantage over counterparts in seasonal climates.',
  'https://images.pexels.com/photos/1325682/pexels-photo-1325682.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
  'Calvia Editorial',
  '2026-01-05T10:00:00Z',
  ARRAY['Lifestyle', 'Sports'],
  'Lifestyle'
),
(
  'Sailing the Southwest Coast: A Beginner''s Guide to Calvia Waters',
  'sailing-calvia-beginners-guide',
  'From day charters to sailing courses, Calvia offers some of the Mediterranean''s finest waters for both novice and experienced sailors. Discover the best routes, charter options, and sailing schools in the area.',
  E'The waters off Calvia''s southwest coast offer ideal sailing conditions for most of the year: reliable thermal winds in summer, moderate seas, and a coastline of extraordinary beauty. Whether you want to learn to sail, charter a boat for the day, or explore the coast under your own command, here is everything you need to know.\n\n## Best Sailing Months\n\nThe sailing season runs from April through October, with June and September offering the best combination of reliable wind and comfortable temperatures. Summer afternoons bring the embat, a consistent thermal sea breeze of ten to fifteen knots that provides perfect sailing conditions. Winter sailing is possible on calmer days and offers solitude impossible to find in season.\n\n## Charter Options from Puerto Portals\n\nPuerto Portals is Calvia''s primary sailing hub, with several charter companies offering everything from small day-sail yachts to crewed luxury catamarans. A typical day charter heads south toward Portals Vells, anchoring in the coves for swimming and lunch, before returning via Illetes in the afternoon.\n\n## Day Route: The Three Coves Circuit\n\nA classic half-day sail from Puerto Portals heads southwest to Portals Vells, rounds the headland to Cala Falco, and returns via El Toro. The route covers approximately twelve nautical miles and passes some of the most impressive coastal scenery in the western Mediterranean. The anchorage at Portals Vells provides good holding in sand and excellent snorkelling.\n\n## Port Adriano Marina\n\nDesigned by Philippe Starck, Port Adriano is Calvia''s newest and most architecturally striking marina. The facility accommodates vessels up to sixty metres and offers full technical support, fuel, and provisioning services. The marina hosts several regattas throughout the season.\n\n## Learning to Sail\n\nSeveral schools based at Puerto Portals and Santa Ponsa offer RYA-accredited courses for adults and children. The consistent conditions and sheltered bay make Calvia an ideal learning environment. Courses range from weekend introductions to week-long competent crew certifications.\n\n## Fishing by Boat\n\nRecreational fishing from a boat requires a licence obtainable online from the Balearic Government. The waters off Calvia hold dentex, amberjack, and in deeper water, bluefin tuna. Several charter operators specialise in fishing trips with all equipment provided.',
  'https://images.pexels.com/photos/1295036/pexels-photo-1295036.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
  'Calvia Editorial',
  '2026-01-02T10:00:00Z',
