(
  'Interior Design Trends: Mediterranean Luxury Redefined',
  'interior-design-mediterranean-calvia',
  'Calvia''s homes are evolving beyond traditional Mediterranean style. A new generation of designers is blending island materials with contemporary minimalism to create interiors that feel both timeless and of the moment.',
  E'The interior design landscape in Calvia reflects a broader evolution in Mediterranean luxury living. Gone are the heavy terracotta and wrought iron cliches; in their place, a sophisticated dialogue between natural materials, clean lines, and the extraordinary light that defines the Mallorcan interior experience.\n\n## The New Mediterranean Aesthetic\n\nContemporary Calvia interiors draw from the island''s material vocabulary — stone, lime, olive wood, linen — while applying a modernist sensibility that prioritises space, light, and restraint. Walls are finished in natural lime plaster that changes character throughout the day as the light moves. Floors of polished concrete or reclaimed stone replace predictable tile choices.\n\n## Colour Palettes\n\nThe dominant palette draws from the landscape: the warm whites and creams of limestone, the green-greys of olive groves, the deep blues of deep water, and the warm ochre of the Mallorcan earth. Accent colours reference the natural environment — the deep pink of bougainvillea, the silver of olive leaves, the warm amber of local sandstone.\n\n## Indoor-Outdoor Integration\n\nIn Calvia, the boundary between interior and exterior is deliberately dissolved. Floor-to-ceiling glass walls retract completely, extending living spaces onto terraces. Outdoor rooms with permanent seating, lighting, and weather protection function as genuine living spaces for eight months of the year. The design of outdoor areas now receives the same attention and budget as interior rooms.\n\n## Sustainable and Local Materials\n\nA growing emphasis on sustainability drives the specification of locally sourced materials. Mallorcan marés sandstone, reclaimed roof tiles, and timber from managed island forests reduce both environmental impact and transportation costs while creating interiors rooted in their geographic context.\n\n## Kitchen and Bathroom Evolution\n\nKitchens in contemporary Calvia homes have become the primary social space. Open layouts, professional-grade appliances, and integrated dining create rooms designed for the Mediterranean lifestyle of communal cooking and long meals. Bathrooms trend toward spa-like environments with walk-in wet rooms, natural stone, and views to private gardens.\n\n## Working with Island Designers\n\nCalvia is home to several internationally recognised interior design studios and a skilled artisan community. The best results come from designers who understand both contemporary design principles and the specific challenges and opportunities of the Mallorcan climate and building traditions.',
  'https://images.pexels.com/photos/1571460/pexels-photo-1571460.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=800',
  'Calvia Editorial',
  '2025-12-18T10:00:00Z',
